The article discusses the United States National Action Plan on Women, Peace, and Security. It highlights the importance of empowering women as equal partners in preventing conflict and building peace in countries affected by war, violence, and insecurity. The plan aims to integrate a gender-responsive approach into the United States' diplomatic, development, and defense-related work in conflict-affected environments. It focuses on objectives such as national integration and institutionalization, participation in peace processes and decision-making, protection from violence, conflict prevention, and access to relief and recovery. The plan outlines specific actions and commitments by various government agencies to achieve these objectives. It also emphasizes accountability and monitoring of progress. The National Action Plan reflects the Obama Administration's commitment to ensuring women's equal role in promoting peace and achieving lasting security.